soln_description:
Solution. We will prove the inequality using mathematical induction. The inequality is true for $n=2$. Indeed, given that $\alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}$ belong to the interval $\left(0^{\circ}, 180^{\circ}\right)$, then

$$
\sin \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}\right)=\sin \alpha_{1} \cos \alpha_{2}+\sin \alpha_{2} \cos \alpha_{1}<\sin \alpha_{1}+\sin \alpha_{2}
$$

Let us assume that the inequality is true for $n=k$, that is, for

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \alpha_{1}, \alpha_{2}, \ldots, \alpha_{k} \text { such that } \alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k} \in\left(0^{\circ}, 180^{\circ}\right) \text { it holds that } \\
& \sin \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k}\right)<\sin \alpha_{1}+\sin \alpha_{2}+\cdots+\sin \alpha_{k}
\end{aligned}
$$

For $n=k+1$, we get that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sin \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\right. & \left.\alpha_{k}+\alpha_{k+1}\right)=\sin \left(\left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k}\right)+\alpha_{k+1}\right) \\
& =\sin \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k}\right) \cos \alpha_{k+1}+\cos \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k}\right) \sin \alpha_{k+1} \\
& <\sin \left(\alpha_{1}+\alpha_{2}+\cdots+\alpha_{k}\right)+\sin \alpha_{k+1} \\
& <\sin \alpha_{1}+\sin \alpha_{2}+\cdots+\sin \alpha_{k}+\sin \alpha_{k+1}
\end{aligned}
$$

from which, according to the principle of mathematical induction, the truth of the inequality for every natural number greater than 1 follows.

